Exercise 12.12
We used a tree-recursive procedure, count-combos, in Section 7.5 to determine
how many ways there were to redeem for prizes the 10 tickets one of our sons won
playing Whacky Gator at the local arcade.

a. Since we wrote Chapter 7, our children have grown older and are better Gator
Whackers. Empirically see how well (or poorly) the tree-recursive count-combos
procedure you wrote in Chapter 7 can accommodate this by seeing how the time
grows as the number of tickets to redeem grows.
b. Write a memoized version, and empirically compare it with your prior version.

answer:
from chapter 7
(define (count-combos prize-list amount)
  (cond [(equal? amount 0) 1] ; used our amount perfectly
        [(null? prize-list) 0] ; prize list is empty, nothing else to pick - return the count.
        [(< amount 0) 0] ; amount <= 0, overspent;
        [else (+ (count-combos prize-list (- amount (car prize-list)))
                 (count-combos (cdr prize-list) amount))]; else, keep exploring the branch

        )
  )
(count-combos '(5 3 1 1) 10)


|#


; part a
; count-combos is not memoiszed and its slow. in recursiv call it calls itself in 2 branch
; giving binary explosion depending on prize list and amount as they go high

; part b: memoized version
(define (memoized-count-combos prize-list amount)
  ; make table that stores a b
  ; make main func and subproblem helper
  ; fill it
  (let ((table (make-table (+ (length prize-list) 1) (+ amount 1))))
    (define (count-combos p a)
      (cond [(equal? a 0) 1] ; used our amount perfectly
            [(null? p) 0] ; prize list is empty, nothing else to pick - return the count.
            [(< a 0) 0] ; amount <= 0, overspent;
            [else (+ (count-combos-subproblem p (- a (car p)) )
                     (count-combos-subproblem (cdr p) a))]; else, keep exploring the branch

            )
      )
    
    ;subproblem helper
    (define (count-combos-subproblem p a)
      (if (< a 0)
          0
          (begin (ensure-in-table! p a)
                 (table-ref table (length p) a))
          )
      
      )

    ; store in table
    (define (store-into-table! p a)
      (table-set! table (length p) a (count-combos p a))
      )

    ; ensure in table
    (define (ensure-in-table! p a)
      (if (table-ref table (length p) a)
          'done
          (store-into-table! p a)
          )
      )

    (table-fill! table #f)
    (count-combos prize-list amount)
    
    )
  )
(memoized-count-combos '(1 2 3 4 5 6 7) 3)

; MEMO VS DP
; memo -> top down
; start at the peak, look down
; on demand. needs 2x below me -> search or those and pick when its needed
; fill table with #f

; DP
; start at foundation
; bottom row -> lay next row up, next
; when its at the peak, everything's there, no jumpming back and forth
; fill table with number

