Exercise 12.20
Write a procedure called make-lines that takes a list of elements and a list of
integers and breaks the list of elements into sublists. For example, (make-lines
’(a b c d e f g h i j) ’(2 3 5)) has a value of ((a b) (c d e) (f g
h i j)). You should assume that the integers in the second list add up to the
number of elements in the first list.

answer:
|#

; assume ints add up/ fits with 1sto ne
; list-of-x list-of-x -> list-of-list-of-x
(define (make-lines elements integers)
  (cond [(null? integers) '()]
        [else (cons (take elements (car integers) )
                     (make-lines (drop elements (car integers) ) (cdr integers) ) ) ]
        )
  )
(make-lines '(a b c d e f g h i j) '(2 3 5))

